The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, May 24, 2004 				 ONGC, RasGas in LNG talks
																								New Delhi, May 23 (PTI): Oil and Natural Gas Corporation (ONGC) is in talks with RasGas of Qatar for sourcing 10 million tonnes of LNG for its Rs 25,000-crore Mangalore project that includes setting up of a 2,500 MW power plant and petrochemicals complex.																								Initial talks with RasGas have been held at New Delhi and Doha. RasGas team has done a first-hand assessment of the demand and a deal is likely to take place soon, ONGC sources said.																								ONGC proposes to invest Rs 5,000 crore by 2008 in setting up a 10 million-tonne LNG import and re-gassification plant and Rs 1,100 crore in a plant to extract C2/C3 (ethane/propane) and LPG from LNG at Mangalore port.																								Around Rs 9,000 crore is planned for setting up a dual feed petrochemical complex at Mangalore based on C2/C3 extracted from LNG and naphtha from Mangalore Refinery and Petrochemicals Ltd, a subsidiary of ONGC.																								Sources said ONGC proposes to use 1.5 million tonnes of LNG for 1,445 MW, Rs 3,200 crore power plant at Mangalore SEZ. Besides, Rs 3,500 crore is lined up for a power plant at Ennore in Tamil Nadu. 
